Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** — it hosts your app in-process with a test HTTP pipeline (no real ports).

### Setup

```csharp
// MyMcpServerTests.cs
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing;
using System.Net.Http.Json;
using System.Text.Json;

public class McpIntegrationTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test-client", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2.0", body.GetProperty("jsonrpc").GetString());
        Assert.Equal(1, body.GetProperty("id").GetInt32());
        Assert.True(body.GetProperty("result").TryGetProperty("capabilities", out _));
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ToolsList_ReturnsRegisteredTools()
    {
        var request = new { jsonrpc = "2.0", id = 2, method = "tools/list" };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        var tools = body.GetProperty("result").GetProperty("tools");
        Assert.True(tools.GetArrayLength() > 0);
    }
}
```

### Key points

1. **`WebApplicationFactory<Program>`** boots your real `Program.cs` startup in-memory — no ports, no process spawning.
2. **`CreateClient()`** gives you an `HttpClient` wired to the in-memory test server.
3. For **SSE transport**, use `CreateClient()` with `HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead` and read the stream:
   ```csharp
   var response = await _client.GetAsync("/mcp/sse",
       HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead);
   using var stream = await response.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync();
   using var reader = new StreamReader(stream);
   var line = await reader.ReadLineAsync(); // "event: ..." / "data: ..."
   ```
4. **Mock dependencies** by overriding DI in the factory:
   ```csharp
   factory.WithWebHostBuilder(builder =>
   {
       builder.ConfigureServices(services =>
       {
           services.AddSingleton<IMyService>(new FakMyService());
       });
   });
   ```
5. Make sure `Program` is accessible — add to your server project:
   ```csharp
   // at bottom of Program.cs (or via InternalsVisibleTo)
   public partial class Program { }
   ```

This gives you full protocol-level coverage (JSON-RPC framing, routing, serialization, error codes) with the speed of an in-process call.
